Her mother had fallen off of a stepping stool while attempting to grab a vase from the highest cabinet they had.

This study was to show that adherence to a “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet), as reflected by a high “alternate Mediterranean (aMed) diet score”, is associated with reduced risk of chronic heart disease (CHD) and stroke and stroke mortality.  The aMed diet is a modified version of the Med diet and is characterized by higher consumption of plant foods, including plant proteins (excluding potatoes, but including fruits, nuts, whole grains and legumes), monounsaturated fat (compared to saturated fat) and fish, and lower consumption of animal products and saturated fats.  Moderate intake of alcohol is allowed.
  	

Prior prospective studies documented an inverse association between adherence to a Med diet and risk of total and cardiovascular (CVD) mortality and an intervention trial showed the Med diet to be more effective than a low-fat diet, in promoting weight loss and lowering the ratio of total to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol in obese individuals.  Prior studies did not focus on stroke or stroke mortality.


This epidemiological study followed 74,886 women, 38 to 63 years of age, without a history of CVD or diabetes, who are participants in the Nurses' Health Study, a cohort study of 121,700 female nurses in 11 US states.  Six times, from 1984 to 2004, the authors computed an aMed diet score from self-reported “food frequency questionnaires” (“FFQs) designed to assess nutrient intake during the preceding year.  More than 95% of nurses continued participation throughout the 20 year period. FFQs were subjected to validation studies.  Reports of CHD, fatal CHD and stroke were confirmed by review of medical or hospital records, autopsy or death certificates. Where records were not available, cases were considered “probable” and included, with about 17% of all strokes and 24% of nonfatal myocardial infarcts so classified. Body mass index, smoking status, aspirin use, multivitamin intake, menopausal status and use of postmenopausal hormone were calculated for each FFQ, and beginning in 1986, leisure-time physical activity was assessed. 

To reduce random variation for an individual and better represent long-term dietary intake, cumulative averages of the aMed score from the repeated FFQs were calculated (averaging together scores from two prior years).  Adjustments were made for “confounders” (factors that could confuse results) by adjusting for age, smoking, BMI, menopausal status, postmenopausal hormone use, multivitamin intake, alcohol intake, physical activity and aspirin use.

Cox proportional-hazard modeling was used to assess the association between an aMed score and risk of CHD and stroke, using separate models for fatal and nonfatal CHD and stroke types. 

Greater adherence to the Mediterranean diet, as reflected by a higher aMed diet score, was associated with a lower risk of incident CHD and stroke in women.  During 20 years of follow-up, 2391 incident cases of CHD, 1763 incident cases of stroke and 1077 cardiovascular disease deaths (fatal CHD and strokes combined) were found. Women in the top aMed quintile were at lower risk for both CHD and stroke compared with those in the bottom quintile (relative risk [RR], 0.71).

In 2007, the United States of America fell into a crushing financial crisis. Unemployment increased, the housing market crashed, and many of America’s largest and most important corportations were left in ruin. This recession persists today, so we must ask the question: how did this crisis occur, and how can we stop it? In short, the financial crisis was created by selfish and naïve political decision-making that pressured banks and firms into issuing sub-prime loans into an already immature and unsufficient financial infrastructure. Meanwhile, Fannie Mae (FNMA) and Freddie Mac (FHLMC) were pressured to underwite and repackage these mortgages into CDO’s and CDS’. When borrowers defaulted on these loans, the banks were short on capital reserve and transferred this chaos onto the repacked mortgages that they had sold, and on to the rest of the economy.
	The financial crisis had its roots in 1999 of the Clinton era, as the President was aiming for a second term in office. He sought to extend his presidential tenure by augmenting his popularity. To accomplish this the Clinton administration relaxed lending restrictions, which helped to set the grim stage for the sub-prime crisis seven years later.  Steven Holmes of the New York Times reported in 1999, “Fannie Mae, the nation's biggest underwriter of home mortgages, has been under increasing pressure from the Clinton Administration to expand mortgage loans among low and moderate income people and felt pressure from stock holders to maintain its phenomenal growth in profits.” Holmes would go on to correctly foresee the consequences of these actions: “But the government-subsidized corporation may run into trouble in an economic downturn, prompting a government rescue similar to that of the savings and loan industry in the 1980s.” As detailed in the introduction, and as Holmes foresaw, ill-advised lending would certainly lead to the meltdown of the economy.
	Many factors combined to throw the economy into tailspin, one of which was the new and complex structure of mortgages. Adjustable-rate mortgages, mortgage-backed securities, and collateralized debt obligations (CDO’s) were all used extensively in the years leading up to the crisis, and only served to intertwine more sectors of the economy into the housing market. This led to U.S. households, and financial markets in general, to overleverage themselves in the housing market, leaving them extremely vulnerable to even small changes in price. 
	Indeed, the housing bubble burst, and the financial institutions that had bought these mortgage-backed securities were spited. The top five U.S. investment banks all together reported $4.1 trillion dollars of mortgage debts in 2007, which accounted for about 30% of the USA’s GDP. In the end, Bear Sterns and Merrill Lynch were sold exceptionally cheap, Lehman Brothers was dismantled, and Goldman Sachs and Morgan Stanley were forced to become commercial banks subjected to intense regulation. Fannie and Freddie were $5 trillion in mortgage debt, and were placed under government control in September 2008.

Ah, exposition.  That place in your story where you stretch your little writer's wings and take flight, astounding one and all with your magnetic, nay magical prose.  Or the part where your readers fall asleep and/or hit the "Back" button while cursing your name.  Dr. Merlin has been known to shout at her monitor when she finds herself in the middle of Too Much Information, and not even in the fun way.

Exposition is not your friend.

My gentle readers already know the basic writing tip, "Show, don't tell," but Dr. Merlin still stumbles into long passages of text where nothing happens, or worse, too much.  Exposition is the little devil sitting on your shoulder that says to get the history out of the way to get to the good parts (not to be confused with the devil sitting on the other shoulder urging the author to tell her audience every single detail of the childhoods of each character).

Exposition means telling the audience what happened, typically in simple prose.  In film, the exposition happens when one character tells another a core-dump of information ala "The Rime of the Ancient Mariner."  In fiction, the author's doing the telling.

An example is in order.  As you are reading a story, you are told that the heroine met her beloved at such a place and time, that they were married in a gala fashion, and that her husband was murdered in front of her eyes.  You would not expect this entire sequence to take two pages, during which time both he and she only get two lines of dialogue each.  You would expect the author to spend some time on the husband's character, evidencing by his speech and manner how deeply he loves his wife, and you would equally expect the heroine to show through big and small ways how much his presence in her life changed and enriched her (especially if the story were to tell you flat out later that this was the case).  A proper introduction to the husband's character would allow you to become emotionally involved with his fate and would give you insight into the heroine's character: what she saw in him, how deep their bond was, clues about her thoughts and beliefs and dreams as reflected through the prism of his eyes, and so on.  You would mourn his death with her, and so grow more connected to the heroine herself.

In short, you would expect meat on the simple bone of the storyline: "They met, they married, he died."

As a writer, you need to provide that meat.  (*looks at metaphor, sighs, plunges onward*)  Sometimes it is tempting to rush past certain things.  Perhaps you're introducing a new character and you know he used to be in the Air Force, and he's the night manager of a gas station now, and he was married twice, no kids, likes to go fishing on the weekends, secretly dreams of owning the gas station someday and had Eggs Benedict for breakfast.

I watched two newscast’s from Columbus, Ohio. The first one that was “live” was NBC 4 this morning (August 13, 2011). The lead story was about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife, it did not state her name however his name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his mug shot and he looked like pure evil. They devoted only about two minutes to this story as it was developing. The only details they provide he had stabbed her multiple times and had been arrested. I think they spent an appropriate amount of time on this story. 
	The second story was about an early morning shooting of Travis Buyers, 18. He was shot in the Sharon Woods area and had been critically injured; there had been no arrests made at the time or any suspects. The SWAT Team was investigating the crime. This story seemed to be short, and I believe that might have been due to the fact this was a “black” man or a black neighborhood. I noticed (and have for years) that minorities are glossed over when they are a victim of a crime. If say a “white” child or adult is kidnapped or missing or a victim of a crime the media goes nuts; but if a minority person it’s lucky if it is even mentioned. 
	The next story was about the gunshot hole that had been found in the Med-Flight helicopter. Details were given about where they thought the incident happened. It had been determined that it was a .22 caliber bullet from a rifle that had hit the helicopter. Crime-Stoppers are offering a five-thousand dollar reward for tips that lead to the arrest of the shooter. 
	The next story was concerning the rain and thunderstorms predicted for Saturday afternoon. They said the temperatures would remain in the mid to low eighties for the weekend. The length of time was a little short, but they wanted to use it as a “teaser” so that you would stay tuned. 
	They also ran with a story about a robbery of a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. They said it was dark-skinned black man who robbed the store he was wearing a hoodie sweatshirt. They said he was about six-foot tall and weighed about one hundred and fifty pounds. I thought they devoted an unusual about of time emphasizing he was black and how dark he was. 
	Another story was about a Rene Rodriguez who was a convicted Texas Drug-Kingpin. He had been convicted of conspiring to distribute marijuana in large amounts to Ohio from Texas. One curious thing I noted, was instead of saying he was sentenced to twenty-five years in prison they said “300” months. I am not sure what the angle was there, whether they thought that sounded more harsh or what. They also mentioned he was a Hispanic man, I don’t believe that was really germane to the story.

There is a bond between brothers; an unbreakable, irrevocable bond. Within that bond lie many emotions: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty, just to name a few. Brothers understand one another, far more than anyone else with that kind of bond, and they can only see themselves when looking at their brother. It is when a situation is at its most dire when the true nature of this bond shines through, be it good or evil. When these emotions become clear, they carry with them great a cost. Part of understanding the emotions born of this fraternal link is dealing with the consequences that they bring. When one can look a brother in the eye and see within that person their own reflection, they see themselves not as others see them, but as they truly are. In their actions and the consequences of those actions is where their true character lies.  In “The Scarlet Ibis”, two brothers explore this theme, and all of the raging emotions that accompany it. Throughout a lush, vividly described landscape, these two boys set out on a futile journey. Bitter disappointment clashes with intense pride in the climactic scene, and only one brother escapes with his life. The theme is expressed through direct characterization of the protagonist, Doodle, and their interactions with each other, as well as through the narrator’s point of view, which communicates the complex feelings experienced by the protagonist and his view of the world around him, both of which are heavy influences on his actions.
	The protagonist’s actions can all be summed up by one key emotion: pride. From the time he and his little brother, Doodle, first go out together, to their final, fateful excursion, the protagonist feels resentment towards Doodle. He had wanted a brother whom he could teach all of his worldly skills, like “…holding my breath, running, jumping, or climbing the vines in Old Woman Swamp…” He wanted a brother who could fill the role of “…someone to race to Horsehead Landing…and someone to perch with in the top fork of the great pine behind the barn…” Obviously these things are impossible, given Doodle’s condition. Doodle was born with an extremely weak heart, making in unlikely he would even survive. Even then, it was nearly impossible that he would ever participate in vigorous physical activity. What a blow to the young protagonist, his head filled with wild fantasies, to have all of those dreams crushed in an instant. In fact, he is even shown to bear some anger towards the small child, as he recalls beginning to contemplate killing him by suffocating him with a pillow. What kind of child would have the presence of mind to consider infanticide? However, his heart melts when the small child smiles at him. Such a simple act gave the protagonist such hope! This shows that his conviction probably was not very strong. In the back of his mind, he had an instinctive love for his brother.

The human brain is a complicated, creative information-processing system. As technology advanced from primitive to modern, the metaphors used to describe the brain also advanced. Initially, it was compared to a wax tablet, then to a sheet of papyrus, then to a book, and most recently, to a computer. As you learn about the brain, keep in mind that the usefulness of these metaphors is limited and can lead to erroneous conclusions.
Information processing starts with input from the sensory organs, which transform physical stimuli such as touch, heat, sound waves, or photons of light into electrochemical signals. The sensory information is repeatedly transformed by the algorithms of the brain in both bottom-up and top-down processing. For example, when looking at a picture of a black box on a white background, bottom-up processing puts together very simple information such as color, orientation, and where the borders of the object are – where the color changes significantly over a short space – to decide that you are seeing a box. Top-down processing uses the decisions made at some steps of the bottom-up process to speed up your recognition of the box. Top-down processing in this example might help you identify the object as a black box rather than a box-shaped hole in the white background.
Once information is processed to a degree, an attention filter decides how important the signal is and which cognitive processes it should be made available to. For example, although your brain processes every blade of grass when you look down at your shoes, a healthy attention filter prevents you from noticing them individually. In contrast, you might pick out your name, even when spoken in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and the results of processing are modulated by attention repeatedly.
In order for the brain to process information, it must first be stored. There are multiple types of memory, including sensory, working, and long-term. First, information is encoded. There are types of encoding specific to each type of sensory stimuli. For example, verbal input can be encoded structurally, referring to what the printed word looks like, phonemically, referring to what the word sounds like, or semantically, referring to what the word means. Once information is stored, it must be maintained. Some animal studies suggest that working memory, which stores information for roughly 20 seconds, is maintained by an electrical signal looping through a particular series of neurons for a short period of time. Information in long-term memory is hypothesized to be maintained in the structure of certain types of proteins.
There are numerous models of how the knowledge is organized in the brain, some based on the way human subjects retrieve memories, others based on computer science, and others based on neurophysiology. The semantic network model states that there are nodes representing concepts, and that the nodes are linked based on their relatedness. For example, in a semantic network, “chair” might be linked to “table,” which can be linked to “wooden,” and so forth.

Aldous Huxley criticizes the upcoming threat of both technology and the capitalistic structure by which it is reinforced through the creation of a dystopia in the novel Brave New World. Its people value community above the individual, and are conditioned from the very beginning to pursue immediate happiness above all else. The citizens are revealed to be pawns in a larger game, confined to one ideology as dictated by the World Controller. By examining the work under the lenses of Marxist theism, one notices the underlying suspicions of the author in regards to the development of aforementioned systems. Frequent terminology in Marxism, such as homogeny and reification, among others, reinforce the idea that Huxley’s novel is a commentary on the faults in the emerging economy from his time on.
Capitalism is satirized through the use of the Marxist thesis known as false consciousness. Essentially, the common citizenry is prevented from knowing true relations to other classes in economic terms, as they are primarily interested in their own gain. It is said to be the result of ideological control of the proletariat and common laborers, something quite obvious by the conditioning of the people in Brave New World. The common classes, Delta, Gamma, etc., have no true will of their own; through hypnopædia the drive to consume, to spend, to indulge is strengthened above all else.  This is manipulated, as previously stated, by the World Controller.  Hegemony, essentially the idea that groups of social classes are dominated by  a separate group of individuals in totality, is obviously used in this case. The lower classes are entirely unaware of the manipulation, quite literally ‘[buying]  into an ideology that supports that structure’ (i.e. capitalism & consumerism). ’ Upper classes are born with the ability to be aware of it but do nothing ; few Alphas or Betas beyond characters like Bernard do much more than likewise accept their place.  In fact, the  interactions of the social classes, as will be discussed  in greater length, are significant indications of the perceived oppression of capitalism.
Relationships between disparate individuals does not exist in Brave New World.  The novel seemingly refuses to distinguish the characters - they are, even  among major characters, lacking depth. Perhaps Huxley is suggesting that the rise of technology and capitalism together deprive man of their free will and expression. Love does not exist, nor do the extremes of any one emotion; rather, interactions are kept superficial, portrayed distinctly through  the males remarks  about women primarily about their physical appearance (i.e. pneumatic quality), and the females’  unashamed  comments about their encounters, so to speak.  Furthermore, each societal class’ complacency with their status in the hierarchy  indicate  the socioeconomic effect of capitalism.  Their absolute obedience of their part in the community is an indication of Marxist thought on the proletariat, who are falsely ensured of their own superiority over all else so long as they continue to consume, to obey, to stay in line with the rest of their peers.

I have been a student here at University Park for about two and a half years now, or four and a half semesters. For many, including myself, getting around on campus can be a problem. My freshman year I was placed in an East Halls dorm room; pretty much the furthest eastward limit of campus, not counting the stadium and Bryce Jordan Center. Traveling from my home in Stuart Hall to classes in such faraway places as Willard building, near the center of campus, could take up to 25 minutes by foot, especially if the weather was bad, as it often is in State College. Speaking to an alum not much older than myself, I learned that not long ago the East Halls dorms were set apart from the rest of the school by huge tracts of unused land. Today that empty space has been filled with sports fields, huge new buildings including the new Creamery and new health services building, and surrounded with apartments. As our campus continues to expand, getting from one place to another becomes more and more difficult. What is the best solution to the problem of mobility? On a college campus, it is the bicycle. But the bike by itself won't solve any problems. Students need to ride them, and the campus needs to be built to suit the needs of bicyclists.
	I was talking to a friend of mine who recently resumed bicycling after a several-year hiatus. He mentioned that he wondered why he ever stopped. “Bikes are great,” he said, “for a few years it wasn’t cool to ride a bike, but it’s the only way to get around.” In addition to being good for your body, bicycling is the most efficient way to travel. A bowl of oatmeal and a little physical exertion will take you 30 miles or more. Like many undergraduates, I now live off campus; just as far from the center of campus as some dorms. The smartest decision I’ve made this year was to buy a bike. Every day, I have class in Thomas building, easily a twenty-five-minute walk from my home. Riding a bike can cut that time down to 5 minutes if I pedal fast enough. The only problem is, Pollock Road is the straightest shot to Thomas building from my house, and it's not always an easy road to travel on, bike or no bike. There are things to be said for walking as well, but personally I’m too busy to walk. If I didn’t have my bike, walking would be my only reliable option for getting to class. Walking to Thomas every day would take an extra 30-40 minutes out of my day. That’s over two and a half hours every week. Add to that all the other time I would have to spend walking to and from other classes, appointments, and etc. That’s more time than I can spare.

I want to study social work to help children with abuse and family problems. I can give the field service, respect, and ethical help. I also want to improve myself and be good for my career. These things are important for social work and for me personally.

I wanted to help people, but I did not know what career to follow. In high school and college, I saw people run from problems and use bad coping ways. This made me want to study psychology at Piedmont College. After I finished, I was not sure where to go next. One day, a friend needed help with a boy who was abused by his parents. I talked to the police and helped them. The parents acted nervous and blamed the boy. After this, I thought about being a social worker.

Social justice is also important. Society says that each person is unique, but it wants everyone to be the same. This is not right. I have fought against unfairness all my life. I will keep doing this in social work.

The paper talks about two models for the sleep disorder insomnia: biological and sociocultural. The biological model looks at family genes and health problems. The sociocultural model looks at how the environment affects sleep, and how this relates to race, ethnicity, and wealth.

The review of insomnia discusses these models and the research that explains them. It also talks about the strengths and weaknesses of these studies.

Sleep disorders can be: primary, related to mental health problems, or caused by health issues or drugs. Primary sleep disorders are dyssomnias and parasomnias. Dyssomnias include insomnia and hypersomnia, while parasomnias include nightmare disorder and sleepwalking disorder. Disorders related to mental health can be linked to clinical or personality disorders.

The biological model for sleep disorders looks at genes, inherited factors, and physical sleep problems. Orexin neurons in the brain control sleep and wakefulness. This study with mice found that GABAB receptors on these neurons cause sleep. If these receptors are blocked, this can make people feel less anxious and sleep more. This shows that sleep problems might be inherited.

The sociocultural model shows that if the sleep problem is inherited, it can affect how people sleep. This can make it hard to do well in school, at work, and in everyday life.

This paper talks about three parts of Central Auditory Processing Disorder (CAPD). First, we define the disorder. Next, we explain how to diagnose it. Finally, we tell how teachers can help students with CAPD in a normal classroom.

CAPD is when the brain cannot properly understand sounds we hear. People with CAPD can hear normally, but their brain has trouble separating words or understanding speech with background noise. The earliest mention of the disorder was in the 1950s. It was called “auditory imperception.” A team of Italian researchers started testing children with this problem in 1954. In 1961, a scientist named Kimura introduced a test to understand how the brain works for this disorder. A conference in 1977 sparked more research on CAPD.

There are many signs of CAPD: not being able to find where sound comes from, having trouble telling different sounds apart, not recognizing sound patterns, not hearing changes in speech, not hearing one sound if another sound comes after it, not understanding sound clues, and not knowing the order of sounds. To diagnose CAPD, doctors must test for auditory skills. This can be done by asking questions, watching how the person responds to sounds, or using special tests. There is no single test that works for everyone, and the cause of CAPD is not known. Some tests use many sounds at once and ask the person to pick out certain ones. Other tests record sounds in the ear and measure how the brain responds.

Twelfth Night shows that hiding can be useful to trick people for a long time. But, in the end, one must stop hiding. Otherwise, one loses their true self.

Stopping a trick can be hard. People may feel alone. They may feel others will not like them anymore.

The story of Viola shows this well. She hides as a man to stay safe in a new place. She tricks Olivia into loving her. She also makes Orsino feel love for her. Olivia does not see that Viola is a woman. Orsino does not see that Viola is a girl.

This story shows that hiding can help people show their true feelings. Olivia and Orsino may have feelings they do not know about. Viola as Cesario makes them face these feelings. Olivia loves Cesario. She then loves Sebastian. She sees Cesario as family, not a lover.

German rule in Africa was very bad. They killed many people, like the Ovaherero and Nama. German colonies were different in how they ruled. In East Africa, the German government made schools for natives. In South West Africa (now Namibia), the government left education to missionaries. They didn't care about African education. They only helped European schools. This had long effects. Many Africans in South West Africa were not educated. Other colonies had more educated Africans. This paper wants to explain why South West Africa was different. There are many books about German colonial education. Most are in German. They describe school systems. Later books compare schools in different colonies. Cohen's book, about South West Africa and East Africa, says the big settler population in South West Africa made their education system different. South West Africa had a good climate, so more Europeans lived there. By 1913, there were 15,000 whites in South West Africa, compared to only 5,336 in East Africa.

Popular music has many genres. It started with just a few, but now there are many, many. Rock, country, jazz, folk, rap, and others have many sub-genres and sub-sub-genres. Heavy metal is one of the most diverse genres. It started 40 years ago. It has many emotions and sounds. Many people make new sub-genres and sub-sub-genres. Now, it is hard to know what is heavy metal.

Heavy metal is a movement. It is like a family of music. People like it because it is loud and has dark sounds. They like it because it is like a story. Many people in metal bands play their instruments very well. They use drugs to make music. They like the feeling of the drugs. The music has dark, strong feelings. This is new in popular music. Many modern bands take their music from the Romantic Era. Here are some lyrics:

"Helter Skelter" is a song with dark feelings. It shows how drugs can make people feel. It is like a story. The Beatles made it to be like the Rolling Stones. They wanted to be as heavy and dark as them.

Henri Rousseau is a famous painter. He was born in France in 1844. He did not have formal training in painting. He worked in a government job until he was forty. The death of his wife and children made him very sad. He started painting to feel better. He dreamed of being known and liked by other artists and art lovers. He struggled with this dream. Should he copy other styles to be accepted? Or should he be himself and make his own path? The painting "The Dream" shows this struggle. It is a picture of a woman in a dream. It also shows Rousseau's own dreams and hopes. He wanted to be like other artists. But he also wanted to be different. This is difficult. He was not like other artists. He did not learn about art in school. He worked hard to be known. He wanted to make his own style, not copy others. He hoped to be liked by people who like art.

Many people think that ethics and beauty are linked. I agree that there is a reason for this. As John Keats says in his poem "Ode on a Grecian Urn", "Beauty is truth, truth beauty." We learn many things in life, but we seem to understand ethics and beauty without being taught. Both are ways to explain, not to give rules.

For example, people talk about what makes art or writing good. They might mention things like colors or story, but these don't explain why something is good. When people talk about their favorite art or story, they often say, "There's just something about it." This "something" can't be fully described.

I think art and ethics both have this "something" that makes them powerful. As Flannery O'Connor says, "A story is a way to say something that can't be said any other way." And as Wittgenstein says, "Ethics cannot be expressed. Ethics is transcendent." This "something" connects art and ethics.

I think art and ethics are closely related because we feel them strongly, even if we can't explain why. This is especially true for literature. As McKean says, "Literature is important to us because of the values we find there."

Germany today is strong. It has a mix of cultures from the Alps to the Baltic Sea. In Munich to Kiel, in Cologne by the Rhine, and in Dresden on the Elbe, you can feel this mix. Germany has many different roots. It comes from many tribes.

Germania is the land of the Germans. The name Germany has many meanings. Some say it came from a tribe called Tungrians. Others say it means "shout" in an old Irish language. Another theory is that it means "spear," as Germans used spears in war.

The early Roman historian Tacitus wrote about the Germans. He said they were not mixed with other races. They came by ship. The Romans did not live in Germania. They went for goods and battles, but mostly went home.

Germans lived on the border of the Roman Empire. They traded and fought with the Romans. They served in the Roman army.

I looked down. My mind was empty. I did not feel anything. I was looking at a picture. Thoughts came and went quickly. I did not have real thoughts. I just saw what I was looking at.
An artist friend told me about a book. The book was called "The New Drawing on the Right Side of the Brain." I wanted to learn to draw since I was six. The book teaches everything about drawing and the brain. One thing it teaches is to put a square frame around a picture. This makes a complicated picture simple.
When I saw a bowl of fruit on a table, I could not think about the frame. I was too amazed. Many artists have special styles. I thought I could be an artist too. That bowl was the start of my drawing. I called it "Work in Brown."
I held my pencil. My hand moved through space. I made shapes with my mind. I drew water in the toilet. I tried to push out the brown package. It would not move.
I used a mop. I tried to push the package again. I thought about the job. I wrapped toilet paper around my hand. I dipped my hand into the water. I was like a mother putting a turkey in the oven.

Young people die in car crashes. This is because many things happen together. The teen brain is not ready for driving. Young drivers have little experience. This causes more crashes, more rollovers, speeding, and going off the road.
Teenagers do worse when they drive with friends. A study shows this. More accidents happen when more teens are in the car.
States try to make teen driving safer by limiting hours and no other teens in the car. But this is not enough. Young drivers cannot handle risks and responsibilities well.
Psychologist Marvin Zuckerman says 18 is too young for a full license. USA Today says he found that teens under 19-20 like to take risks. So, it makes sense to delay driving until this changes.
If we keep giving licenses to young teens, more deadly crashes will happen. In a few years, many young drivers will be on the road. We can make a new law. Schools can teach driver safety, but no one under 18 can drive. A permit can be given before a full license. The number of training hours can be like in most states. This law can protect teens in all states. This idea is not new.

I looked at the old films in the Library of Congress. I found fifteen trick films from 1895 to 1901. These films use creative editing to make illusions. My study mostly looked at how the trick films work, and how they change over time. Most trick films from that time are set in one place, with no camera movement. They use long and medium shots, and follow the rule that one shot is one film. Some films break these rules, using multiple shots. Most trick films are set in a stage-like area. The camera does not move to follow actors or objects. Actors move side to side, not towards or away from the camera. For example, in the film Uncle Josh in a Spooky Hotel (1900), actors move from right to left. The camera does not follow them. The films use long shots and medium shots, not close-ups. Actors do not move towards the camera, so close-ups do not happen. Most early trick films are short, about a minute or less. They show tricks, like magic or disappearing acts, with little story. However, one trick shot can show several photos joined together. For example, in The Execution of Mary, Queen of Scots (1895), Mary’s head seems to disappear. It is actually many photos joined together.

John Taylor from Caroline was a early and strong supporter of Republicanism. He was mainly a farmer, but his time in politics made him known for strongly talking about people's freedoms and government. His belief in farming shaped almost all his ideas about government. He wanted to keep and grow the best jobs.

Taylor thought the United States had a chance to make a perfect system because there were no old traditions to stop them. He believed in natural rights, and that all are important. They should not be controlled by the government. He said that in nature, the strongest and smartest can take advantage. But in a society, it should not be like that.

To make a good society, Taylor thought the government must understand the good and bad in people. He believed strongly in two good and two bad sides. He said good principles protect property, help farming, and stop capitalism. A good government based on these principles would work fairly, even if led by people who want more money. Self-interest is not always bad, but it is wrong if it hurts others. A good government is needed to control people's badness, but it must be careful.

Taylor, like many other Republicans, wanted a strict reading of the Constitution. He wanted a small government with only the powers clearly stated. He knew big governments could be bad. But he thought a simple reading could be wrong. He also thought the Declaration of Independence was the true rule of the United States, not just the Constitution.

Look at Figure 17. In the third month, commuter log submissions were very low. This was upsetting. Winter in New England makes it harder to commute by bicycle or on foot. Also, students are busy with schoolwork and grades in December. The busy holiday season and winter break make it easy for people to forget about commuting. We had a special event in March, the Carpool Challenge Week, to try and make commuting more fun. This helped to increase the number of logs. We gave out gifts like restaurant coupons and bookstore gift cards to encourage alternative commuting. It would have been interesting to see if bigger prizes like cars would make more people participate. In the future, we could make prizes bigger to keep people's interest.

An ETF is a type of investment that tracks a group of stocks, but trades like a stock. It offers benefits like diversification and low costs. But, you must pay a fee for each trade. Many types of ETFs are available.

It's important to check if the benefits of an ETF are real. For this task, we will look at the IHF ETF and compare it to its top 10 holdings. We will see if owning the ETF is better than owning the top 10 stocks alone.

We will only look at the top 10 holdings, which make up 63.58% of the ETF. Below is the list with their percentages.

To see how well the top 10 stocks represent the ETF, we will calculate their contribution to a portfolio's Beta and Return. We will compare these to the ETF's Beta and Return.

The chart shows that the top 10 holdings have a higher return (6.11%) and a lower Beta (.12) than the ETF. This suggests that the top 10 stocks could provide better results. However, we need to check if this difference is real.

To do this, we will find the standard deviation of each top 10 stock and compare it to the ETF's standard deviation.

Poe used "Thulé" in "Dream-Land". He got this word from Virgil. Virgil used it to talk about an island north of Britain. Poe liked German authors. He knew about Goethe. In "The King of Thulé," Goethe wrote about a king losing his wife. The king drinks a lot and dies. Poe used "Thulé" twice in his poems. He used "ultma Thulé" in "The Pit and the Pendulum". Both "The King of Thule" and "Dream-Land" can be read together. In "Dream-Land", the speaker describes a dark, lonely place. He sees dead friends and a world without color. This is like the king in Goethe's poem. Poe respected Tennyson. Tennyson liked Goethe. Poe would have known Goethe's work.

In California, a customer who slips and falls can get special damages if the store manager acts badly. To win punitive damages, a person must show the manager did something bad on purpose or without care. Martin did not clean the spill even after being told twice because he was eating. This is bad. Others had slipped before. Martin did not act to keep the store safe. A judge will not quickly throw away Palmer's claim. She can show Martin knew the spill could hurt people and did not do anything. Six people slipped in 2009. Martin did not fix the problem. In California, a person can get punitive damages if the store manager acts with bad intent or without care. Martin's actions were careless and bad.

Four years ago, I studied Islam at CBC. We talked about if Islam is a bad religion. I think this is more important today. After 9/11, mass media changed. First, they were unfriendly to Islam. Then, they were very friendly. In 2001, no one could imagine a president named Barack Obama with Muslim family.

The story of Muhammad is interesting. It does not seem true. Muhammad forced people to become Muslims. But the story says he was a peaceful man. People came to him and learned about his teachings.

There are similarities between Jesus' and Muhammad's stories. Muhammad turned little food into much food for many men. This makes me think the story of Muhammad is not true. It makes Jesus seem less important.

Many stories in the book say people saw the truth of Islam on their own. But these stories are told by people who heard from others. This makes the stories seem less true.

I do not like that the book makes Muhammad seem like a good, humble man. History shows Muhammad was not so humble. I think Muslims today should learn the true story of Muhammad.

Jesus' teachings and beliefs were not followed after his life. Christian thought changed over time. Today, many people want to learn more about the original teachings of Jesus. In the future, more Christians will understand these teachings. This will happen slowly, taking years or even hundreds of years. They will remove extra beliefs, like layers of a cake, until only Jesus' original teachings are left. This will happen in the United States and Europe. The church will lead this change. Beliefs will become more similar between different groups. People will read Jesus' words as metaphors, not as literal statements. Before Jesus, there was only Judaism. The Romans controlled Jerusalem in 63 B.C.E. Jews had different beliefs: Sadducees, Pharisees, Essenes, Zealots, and a large group of common people.

I think that The Jungle shows that people are naturally selfish and only care about themselves. They want to make their lives better, but they do not help others. The Jungle shows this in many ways. The owners and managers of big factories only want to make their companies and factories big. They do not care about anyone or anything that gets in their way. Sinclair shows that the owners do not care about the smoke and waste from the factories. They also do not care about their workers.

The owners and managers want to make money. They do not care about their workers. They make their workers work much and then lay them off without warning. There were no laws to protect workers then. The workers had no help. Unions did not help. Workers were treated like slaves. They worked and lived in terrible conditions. They could not escape.

Some writers use different methods to make readers feel or think about important topics. Some of these methods work better than others. F. Scott Fitzgerald uses these methods in his book The Great Gatsby. He pairs words that do not usually go together to give readers a certain mood. He also gives special meanings to symbols, then uses them to do this.

Fitzgerald uses color to give special meanings. He uses gold, green, white/gray, and red/pink colors. In The Great Gatsby, he makes white/gray mean uniformity. White is for upper class, and gray is for older, faded things. At the start of the book, Fitzgerald uses white and gray often. Daisy and Jordan are always in white. People wear white to parties. Nick wears white to Gatsby's party. Tom wears a white shirt. Catherine is white. Only when Nick sees Gatsby's party are there other colors.

Fitzgerald uses gray and white for common things. Gray and white are for common people and places. Gray and white are for unimportant things. After giving these meanings to gray and white, Fitzgerald uses them to show that some things, like Daisy, are unimportant. He first shows Daisy in white and a white car. This makes her seem like just something Gatsby wants. Later, he shows Daisy in gray and white clothes to make her seem unimportant.

San Diego County grows many things because it has a mild, warm climate. Common crops include tomatoes, citrus fruits, leafy greens, squash, broccoli, herbs, peaches, lemons, berries, honey, and peppers. Many people in San Diego want organic food. Some farms let people tour and do activities like hiking and birdwatching. Some farms may need help from the government to save money and help wildlife.

Organic farming helps nature by not using chemicals. But it needs more work and can have more losses. It also needs more labor for things like planting cover crops and removing invasive species. Farmers might need help to make more money and improve wildlife.

The chosen land is near the town of Potrero in unincorporated San Diego County. It is 160 acres with chaparral, non-native grassland, and oak trees near the Cleveland National Forest. Many animals live here, some are endangered like the Stephens' kangaroo rat and mountain yellow-legged frog. The land was used by Native Americans and then cattle ranchers.

The farmer wants to farm this land and use government programs to save money and help wildlife. They found a model farm in the same area.

Culture is important in any negotiation. Culture is not one thing, but many things. It is not the same everywhere. Saying "all Russians are stubborn" or "all Japanese are nice" is not true. It is better to understand the meaning of a culture and how it affects negotiations. When you meet a new culture, you compare it to your own. To understand a culture, study its history or find out its beliefs. Do not judge or try to change it. Accept it and use it to your advantage, especially if you are weaker in the negotiation. Respect traditions and beliefs to overcome cultural barriers. Culture is not only about countries. Companies have their own cultures. A company's culture can include long work hours or a relaxed schedule. Company culture can be seen in how people dress, how they talk, and how they hire. Some companies encourage helping others. Others only let employees help approved charities. Culture can be different within a country too. Some cultures are not as divided as American culture. But even cultures that seem the same on the outside have differences. Values are important. They tell why a culture does things. If a culture values saving face, a negotiator will not publicly shame others to win. If a culture values a hard bargain, a negotiator will not settle early. Learn about your opponent's personal culture to make negotiations better.

The Bible says, "The fool says, 'There is no God.'" This quote is in Psalm 14. It starts St. Anselm's argument about God's existence. Thomas Aquinas also believes in God's existence. We will compare their arguments. Both are defending the same idea of God. We will assume they are right in their belief in the Bible's God. We will focus on their arguments about God's existence.

St. Anselm's argument says that God exists in our minds. We cannot imagine God not existing. God's proof is in our own minds. This is called faith in Christianity. It means believing without proof.

Thomas Aquinas says God's existence can be proven by reason and evidence. He has five arguments: change, causation, contingency, degrees of excellence, and harmony. Each shows that God's existence is necessary.

Sometime, a prince became Buddha. He taught about enlightenment. Many people followed his teachings. Now, there is a religion called Buddhism. The main part is called Theravada Buddhism. It is about 2,500 years old. Today, it is different from how it was when Buddha was alive. One example is Sri Lanka. There, people do a water-cutting ceremony. Both monks and laymen go to this. It is a religious event, but Buddha did not teach about it. Theravada Buddhism changes over time because of many reasons. Some are from inside the Buddhist community. Some are from outside. Some are helpful. Some are harmful.
	In this talk, we will use some special words. Internal forces are from Buddhists. External forces are from non-Buddhists. Hostile forces want to harm Buddhism. Benign forces do not want to harm or help Buddhism.
	First, we need to learn about the main ideas of Theravada Buddhism. Buddhists find refuge in the Buddha, the Dhamma, and the Sangha. The Dhamma has three parts: the Sutta Pitaka, the Vinaya Pitaka, and the Abhidhamma Pitaka. The Sutta Pitaka has many Suttas. The Vinaya Pitaka has rules. The Abhidhamma Pitaka has deep ideas. Important ideas include Anatta (no soul), Dukkha (suffering), and Anicca (impermanence). Knowing these ideas helps end Sansara (the cycle of death and rebirth). When people become enlightened, they stop having lobha (desire), dosa (hatred), and moha (delusion). The Vinaya Pitaka has rules for monks and laymen. For laymen, there are five rules. For monks, there are many more rules. The most important idea in Buddhism is the four noble truths. First, life is suffering. Second, attachment causes suffering. Third, suffering can be ended.

The United States and Mexico were rivals for 57 years. From 1836 to 1893, they had many problems. The biggest problem was the Mexican-American War in 1846-1848. The United States won. They got Texas and the Southwest as new land. There were many other problems between the two countries. They stopped having problems before World War I. The problems started because of different beliefs, like religion and culture. They also had different goals, like money. Many other countries near the United States also had problems with their neighbors. Mexican and American problems were like this. David M. Pletcher says that Mexico and Cuba had long problems with the United States. Other Latin American countries had good relations with the United States. Sally Frahm says that Americans were against Catholicism and monarchy in the 18th and 19th centuries. This was like the Cold War between the United States and the Soviet Union. The United States and Mexico had problems because of their religions. They also had problems because of the bad feelings between the English and Spanish. Diehl and Goerts list 17 problems between Mexico and the United States. Most problems were about borders and raids. Raids stopped when both countries used their military. Schmitt says the rivalry stopped when Mexico became dependent on the United States. It stopped because the United States changed their goals from getting land to helping Mexico with money.

Fifteen years ago, I suddenly got sick. I did not know I had this illness.

I was a nurse. I chose this job because I wanted safety and security. I thought, "There will always be jobs for nurses. People get sick."

Even though I dreamed of being a scientist or journalist, I chose nursing.

When I was 46, I could not work anymore. I got Social Security Disability. I have no money left.

Every day is hard. I need help from family and friends. Without them, I would not have made it.

There are always emergencies. Some are too big to handle alone.

We need to trust each other. We should learn to help each other.

Conservatives talk about "rugged individualism." But our ancestors did not succeed alone. They helped each other.

I am prepared. I have a disaster kit. I have water and food. But I also know my neighbors.

Organisms change over time. What rules or rules stop this change? In 1917, D'Arcy Thompson said that even now, scientists cannot define organic shapes in math. But, now, math is used in mollusk skeletogenesis through growth and history. Our study looks at how math and experiments can help us understand how evolution happens. We used X-ray images of Prunum species to find out how shells grow. We used CerioShell software to model these shells. Our results help us understand big changes in this group of animals.

A shell is like a tube that moves around in space. It has many turns called whorls. Each whorl is like a spiral around an imaginary line. This line is called the columella. The shell grows bigger at different speeds. A line between each whorl is called a suture. The last whorl is the biggest. The part of the shell with all the old whorls is called the spire. The top of the spire is the apex. The bottom is the base. The animal comes out of its shell through an opening called the aperture.

We can look at shells in different ways: from the top, bottom, open side, or closed side. The normal way is to see the aperture and apex from the open side.

To count whorls, first look at the shell from the top. Find the first suture and draw a line. Count each whorl from this line. A shell is a series of apertures that move through time and space as the animal builds its shell. We can trace the path of the aperture using coordinates of the center of each whorl's aperture and its horizontal and vertical radius.

We can draw this path and change math to see how changes happen.

Indonesia's neonatal and infant death rates stayed the same for ten years. Indonesia is close to many Millennium Development Goals. It has good water and sanitation. But, child and maternal health are not improving much. The reasons for this are many. They show that the health system needs to be stronger, not just small programs.

Indonesia has more births with skilled workers. Now, 72% of births have skilled workers. But, this includes traditional workers like midwives who cannot help with complicated pregnancies. So, many mothers die from bleeding. Also, fewer children under five are treated for diarrhea by health workers. Postnatal care is not good. Many babies do not get it.

Cesarean-section rates are low, about 4%. In cities, the rate is 7%. In rural areas, it's 2%. This shows that healthcare is better in cities. The poor have less access to healthcare. They may not see a doctor because it costs money.

To improve care, Indonesia should decide if it should focus on programs or strengthen the whole health system. Both methods are good. Programs can fix specific problems quickly. But, programs can also make funding and resources for other areas worse. Programs can also duplicate services and make paperwork worse.

Victorian novels focus on details and the rich people of the time. Two novels, Oliver Twist and Wuthering Heights, are different. They have mystery and strange things. This makes the characters more interesting and shows what they feel.

“Many confusing thoughts came into his mind. He thought he was walking with Sikes and Crackit. They argued angrily. When he looked, he talked to them. Suddenly, he heard gunshots. There were lights and loud noises. He felt like someone carried him away. He felt pain and fear. He was not in control.”

In Oliver Twist, strange dreams show what Oliver feels inside. When he dreams about the shooting, he feels powerless. He cannot save himself. He feels broken, like Fagin has made him give up.

“One day passed. There was no day. Night came. It was long and short. It was full of bad silence and quick dreams.”

Two years ago, I worked in an after school program. I helped students who had trouble with schoolwork. My best subjects were English and reading. I helped a boy named Adrian who had trouble reading. He was in third or fourth grade. He could speak English well, but he had strange problems with reading. Some letters he knew, but others he did not. I found out that his problem was he did not know the English alphabet well. His mother could only speak Spanish. I did not speak Spanish well, but we tried to communicate. I think Adrian is doing better now.

I tell this story to talk about the language barrier in schools. It is important to think about how this can happen, even if a child speaks English well. Reading English can still be hard. In Adrian's case, he just needed help with the alphabet and pronunciations. But for children who speak little English, the solution is more complicated. There is no one solution. We can try different things like dual language programs, mainstream immersion, private tutors, ESL classes. We need to use all of these things together.

First, the dual language system is good for all children, not just those who speak Spanish first. Children in these programs do better in school. Many people think this is a waste of resources. They think only a few children will benefit. That is not true. If we use these programs more, all children will benefit. How can we do this? We do not need all teachers to be bilingual. That would be hard. But we can have special helpers or tutors who speak two languages.

Since we are children, many people tell us there is something big outside of us. Some go to school for this. Others go to church or look inside themselves. Many accept what parents teach them. But some do not believe in this. They think only about their own world. Some change their beliefs. It is important to find what we think about this. We look for light to guide us. We want to find hope in darkness.

My father said, "A cardinal," when I asked about his favorite bird. We sat on the porch, listening to rain. We smoked cigarettes. The gutters brought rain down, wetting plants. He looked out, thinking, remembering. He was thin. His hair was less. He did not look at me. I felt alone, afraid. I hugged him, sat near. We watched rain.

My father died in December, five days after my birthday. Medicine did not help him. He suffered longer than doctors thought. I did not want to watch him die. I remembered him by how he lived. I did not want to see him suffer. I waited alone in bed for news.

No one called me.

The Gothic Novel is an old-new mix. It has been liked and not liked. It is praised for the "terrible sublime" feeling it gives. The first Gothic Novel, The Castle of Otranto, uses old and new ideas to create the Gothic genre. It uses old theater and new nature mimicry. It also uses old medieval ideas. The word "gothic" means old and not modern. But the Gothic Novel stays popular because it is old and new to readers in the future. One main idea in Gothic Novels is Chivalry. In The Castle of Otranto, Chivalry is shown. It is the idea of a brave, honorable knight. The writer, Walpole, thought modern people did not have these good traits. He wanted to show that the old Gothic world was better. He wrote this in a time of political trouble. He hoped to improve the modern world. In his writing, a character named Frederic shows Chivalry. He is a prince. He has suffered. And he is thought to be killed by infidels. He shows the old idea of a gallant, courteous Knight.

Supply chain management is the process of moving goods from order to customer. It was created in 1982 by Keith Oliver. It includes planning, doing, and controlling the supply chain to meet customer needs quickly and well. There are six important parts of a supply chain: making, getting, keeping, place, moving, and information.

First, we have the making part. This is the start of the process. It includes deciding when, why, where, and how to make things. Managers need to know what customers want. They can look at the market to understand this. After understanding the market, managers decide what and how much to make. They also choose where to make it, thinking about volume and quality. After deciding, they focus on workload and equipment.

The second important part is getting. This means choosing which company or partner to work with. A company might have many production divisions. Managers choose the best one for each part of the product. They might also decide to outsource work to other companies to make it faster and cheaper.

Ellen Page stands outside with sign. Sign says "Hitler alive in Burma".
Burma is a country in Southeast Asia. It was ruled by a strong government since 1962. People protested in 2007. Protests were led by monks. Monks wore yellow robes. This is called the "Saffron Revolution".
People started to join the protests. Government let monks meet at first. Then, the military attacked monasteries. Many monks were killed. A journalist was also killed. The government did not tell the truth about the deaths.
This is not new. Many leaders want complete power. They do not like people who think differently. They use force to control people. Early Roman leaders said they were chosen by gods. Japanese leaders are believed to be gods. Our current president talks to a leader of a group called Stupid People.
Some examples are:
- Tiananmen Square protest in China in 1989. Many people were killed.
- Rwanda genocide in the 1990s. Many people were killed because of their race.
- Hitler's time in Germany. Many Jews were killed.

Duke Ellington's music lasted a long time. He was very good at composing and leading his band. His piano playing was not always the main part of his music. Instead, he wrote complex pieces that showed the special skills of his band members. Ellington gave band members room to improvise and play their own parts. He also created unique sounds for the whole band. This was how he made some of the best jazz music. The Grove Music dictionary mentions his use of voice as a "jazz instrument" in his song "Creole Love Call." This song shows his skill at using voice to add color and texture. In this song, the voice starts smoothly and then becomes rougher. There is also a trumpet solo with blue notes. Another part has a high clarinet solo with piano. The whole band repeats the first part. The end has a vocal run and a funny trombone sound. This use of voice to add tone is a big part of Ellington's music. In "Hot and Bothered," Ellington uses tight orchestration and tone color. "It Don't Mean a Thing (If It Ain't Got That Swing)" shows his use of a trombone player to introduce the melody. This shows his ability to use different instruments to create unique sounds.

She always felt like she needed something. She wanted a person, not a thing. She was 14 when this feeling started. It is still there at 17. She has no interest in boys. Some boys tried to talk to her, but they did not appeal to her. She does not know why. She lives life, wondering about her desires.

Yesterday was usually peaceful. Her parents are calm. They rarely argue. They only argue when she wants to be free. She is likeable because she is nice and fun. Today was not peaceful. She heard her mother scream in the kitchen. She ran to help. Her mother was in pain. She helped her mother into the car and drove to the hospital.

The hospital smelled of disinfectant and sickness. She did not feel fear. She was too busy helping her mother. She brought her mother to the doctors. They took her mother away. Her mother fell from a step stool while trying to get a vase.

This research shows that following the “Mediterranean Diet” (Med diet) is good for health. The diet is high in plant foods, monounsaturated fats, and fish, and low in animal products and saturated fats. A little alcohol is okay.

Earlier studies found that the Med diet helps prevent heart disease and death. They did not focus on stroke.

This study looked at 74,886 women, aged 38 to 63, in the Nurses' Health Study. They filled out food questionnaires six times from 1984 to 2004. Over 95% kept filling them out for 20 years. Medical records were checked for heart disease and stroke. Other factors like weight, smoking, and exercise were also noted.

The average diet score was used to show long-term eating habits. Adjustments were made for other factors that might confuse the results.

The study found that following the diet lowers the risk of heart disease and stroke. Over 20 years, 2391 heart cases and 1763 stroke cases were found. Women who followed the diet closely had lower risk.

In 2007, the United States had a big problem with money. Many people lost their jobs. Home prices fell. Big companies had big problems. This problem still exists today. We need to know how it happened and how to stop it.

The problem started with bad decisions by politicians. They made rules that let banks give loans to people who could not repay. These loans were called sub-prime loans. The banks did not have enough money to cover these loans. They made these loans into new things called CDOs and CDS. When people did not pay back, the banks had no money. This caused more problems in the economy.

The problem started in 1999. President Clinton wanted to stay in office. He made rules easier for banks to give more loans. A reporter said this would cause big problems. It did. The reporter was right.

Many things happened that made the problem worse. Mortgages that changed with interest rates, mortgage-backed securities, and CDOs. These things made the economy more connected to the housing market. Many people and banks had too much debt. When the housing market crashed, everyone was hurt.

Banks had $4.1 trillion in mortgage debt. This was a lot of money for the U.S. economy. Some banks were sold cheap. Others failed. Fannie Mae and Freddie Mac had $5 trillion in mortgage debt and were put under government control.

Exposition is in your story. It is where you show your writing skills. But it can bore readers. Dr. Merlin gets angry when she finds too much exposition.

You know the writing rule, "Show, don't tell." But Dr. Merlin still has long passages with no action. This is bad exposition. It is like a small devil on your shoulder saying, "Get the history out of the way."

Exposition is telling what happened. In film, one character tells another. In fiction, the author does the telling.

Example: In a story, you read that a heroine met her husband. They married and he was murdered. You don't expect this to take two pages. You want to see them interact. You want to see their love grow.

As a writer, you must add details. It is tempting to rush through parts. Maybe you know a character was in the Air Force and now manages a gas station. Don't just say this. Show it. Show his life, his dreams.

Don't just present the skeleton of the story. Add meat to it.

I watched two news reports from Columbus, Ohio. The first was a live broadcast from NBC 4 on August 13, 2011. It talked about a man in Ashley, Ohio who had stabbed his wife. Her name was not said. The man's name was Shad Hostettler. They showed his photo, which looked scary. They talked about this story for two minutes, which seemed fine. The second story was about a young man named Travis Buyers, 18, who was shot in Sharon Woods. He was badly hurt. The police were looking for the shooter. This story was short. I think the crime was not important enough. The next story talked about a hole in a Med-Flight helicopter. It was from a .22 caliber rifle bullet. The police are offering five thousand dollars for help in finding the shooter.

The next story talked about rain and thunder for Saturday afternoon. They said the weather would be between 70 and 80 degrees. They wanted to keep people watching for more. They also talked about a robbery at a Clime Road UDF in Columbus. The robber was a dark-skinned black man, about six feet tall and 150 pounds. They talked a lot about his skin color and height.

Another story was about Rene Rodriguez. He was a drug kingpin from Texas. He was put in jail for 300 months for selling lots of marijuana to Ohio. They said he was Hispanic. I don’t think this was important.

There is a strong bond between brothers. It is very difficult to break. This bond has many feelings: love, pride, jealousy, and cruelty. Brothers understand each other better than others. They see themselves in their brothers. The bond shows true feelings in hard times. It can be good or bad. This bond has costs. It is important to understand the feelings and actions it brings. When one looks at a brother, they see their true self, not how others see them. This is shown in "The Scarlet Ibis". Two brothers explore this bond. They go on a difficult journey. In a big moment, disappointment and pride meet. Only one brother survives. The story shows the bond through the main character, Doodle, and his actions. The narrator shows the complicated feelings Doodle has and his view of the world. This influences his actions.

The main character feels pride. From their first adventure, he wants to teach his brother many skills. He wants a brother who can do exciting things with him. But Doodle is weak. He has a small heart. He can't do these things. This is hard for the main character. He gets angry and thinks about killing Doodle. But Doodle smiles at him! This makes the main character feel hope. He loves his brother.

The brain is very complicated. It is a system that processes information. As technology changed, the ways we describe the brain changed too. First, we said it was like a wax tablet. Then, it was a sheet of papyrus. Then, it was like a book. Now, we say it is like a computer. Remember, these descriptions are not perfect and can cause mistakes.
Information starts when the sensory organs get signals. These signals are from touch, heat, sound, or light. The brain changes these signals. It does this in two ways: bottom-up and top-down. Bottom-up means the brain uses simple information to make decisions. For example, when you look at a picture, the brain uses color, shape, and borders to decide it is a box. Top-down means the brain uses decisions from before to make new decisions faster. For example, the brain might say a shape is a box, not a hole.
The brain also has an attention filter. It decides if information is important. For example, when you look at your shoes, you don't notice every blade of grass. But, you can hear your name in a noisy room. There are many stages of processing, and attention changes them.
To store information, the brain uses different types of memory. There is sensory memory, working memory, and long-term memory. Information is first encoded. There are different ways to do this for different types of signals. For example, words can be encoded by what they look like, sound like, or mean. Once information is stored, it must be kept. Some studies say working memory uses loops of electrical signals. Long-term memory might use certain types of proteins.
There are many ways to think about how the brain organizes knowledge. Some ways are based on how people remember things, others are based on computer science, and others are based on the brain's physical structure. The semantic network model says there are nodes for concepts. These nodes are linked based on how related they are. For example, "chair" can be linked to "table," which can be linked to "wooden."

Aldous Huxley talks about the danger of technology and capitalism in his book, Brave New World. The people live in a society where they value the group more than the individual. They are made to want happiness now instead of later. They are like pieces in a game controlled by the World Controller. From a Marxist view, Huxley is worried about how these systems work. He uses ideas like homogeneity and reification to show the problems with the economy.

In Brave New World, capitalism is shown in a bad way. The people do not know about the real economic system. They only think about their own gain. The World Controller controls them. The common people, Delta, Gamma, etc., do not have their own will. They want only to consume and spend. This is because the World Controller makes them want it. The lower classes do not know they are being controlled. The upper classes know but do nothing. Most Alphas and Betas, like Bernard, just accept their place. The way the social classes interact shows how capitalism is like oppression.

In Brave New World, there are no deep relationships. The characters do not have much personality. Maybe Huxley is saying that technology and capitalism take away people's free will and emotions. Love does not exist. People only talk about physical appearance. Everyone is happy to stay in their place in the hierarchy. This shows how capitalism works.

I have been at University Park for two and a half years, or four and a half semesters. Moving around campus can be difficult for many students, including me. When I arrived, I lived in East Halls, the farthest east dorms. The Willard Building is near the center of campus. Walking from Stuart Hall to the Willard Building can take up to 25 minutes, especially in bad weather.

Speaking with an alum, I learned that East Halls used to be far from the rest of the school. Now, there are sports fields, new buildings, and apartments. As the campus grows, it becomes harder to get around.

The best solution is to ride a bicycle. But there must be places for bikes and safe paths for cyclists. I have a friend who rode his bike after a long break. He says bikes are the best way to get around. They are good for your body and fast.

I live off-campus now, far from the center. Buying a bike was the best decision this year. I go to Thomas Building every day. Walking would take 30-40 minutes. Riding a bike cuts that time to 5 minutes. The only problem is, Pollock Road is not always easy to ride on. Walking would take extra time. Without a bike, walking would be my only choice. That’s more than two and a half hours a week. That’s too much time.

In pursuing an education in social work, I intend to follow a career path with the Division of Family and Children Services to help children who have been abused or neglected; and to provide support for troubled families. Values that I can provide to the social work field include the following: service, respect, ethical nature, commitment to help improve relationships between others and to improve myself professionally to remain competent in my field. These core values are not just important to social workers; they are important to me personally. 

	I have always wanted to help others, but I was unsure of the career path that I wanted to follow. Throughout my years in high school and college, I saw many individuals flee from their problems in denial and a few used coping mechanisms that were less than ideal. Because of situations that I have witnessed, I chose to pursue a Bachelor’s degree in Psychology. Still unsure of a career path, I decided to take a break once I graduated from Piedmont College in 2009. One day that summer, I visited a friend who introduced me to a sixteen year-old boy sitting nervously on her couch. She explained to me why he was visiting: to escape his abusive parents. The next day, I learned that he had called the police to his parent’s residence. To see if I could help in any way, I drove over to his parents’ house. Once there, I privately explained my concerns to the police and told them I had just graduated with a degree in Psychology from Piedmont College. The police requested that I talk to the parents since there was nothing that the law could do for the teenager. When I questioned the parents about the situation, they seemed nervous and used excuses to describe their son’s “manipulative” behavior for involving outside sources to resolve “simple” disputes. After this particular experience, I began to seriously consider a career in social work to help children with “simple” disputes among family members.

	Another value that is important for the field of social work is social justice. As a society, we claim that the individual is important and we mourn those that we have lost. The concept of the “individual” that society holds is more a follower of archaic traditions than actual uniqueness. So, if society mourns lost individuals, then why do we strive to be similar to “everyone else?” I am an individual and do not enjoy placing limitations on myself to be similar to others. Throughout my years at high school and college, I protested against social injustice whenever I could: coloring my hair unnatural colors, wearing clothing that fit my personality, piercing my ears past the traditional set, declaring my involvement with GSBA (Gay Straight Bisexual Alliance), fighting against both racism and discrimination whenever I witnessed it, etc. I believe in social justice and I will continue to protest against social injustice.

The following paper addresses the Biological and Sociocultural models in relation to the disorder insomnia. The biological model focuses on genetic information that is inherited as well as medical aspects of health. The Sociocultural models look at environmental relationships and their applications to race, ethnicity, demographics, and socioeconomic status. The following review of insomnia looks at these models and explains each piece of research chosen to relate to and to better explain the models. The explanations of the research and their findings are then critiqued to mention their specific strengths and weaknesses.

A sleep disorder can be characterized as a primary sleep disorder, a sleep disorder related to another mental disorder, or a sleep disorder related to other issues. The Primary sleep disorders are Dyssonmias or Parasomnias while sleep disorders related to another mental disorder are related to an Axis I or Axis II disorder. Other categories of sleep disorders can be due to medical complications or the intake of a substance. The Dyssomnias are: Primary Insomnia, Primary Hypersomnia, Narcolepsy, Breathing- Related Sleep Disorder, Circadian Rhythm Sleep Disorder, and Dyssomnia Not Otherwise Specified (NOS). While Primary Insomnia is a complication in adequate or maintained sleep, Primary Hypersomnia is a difficulty in staying awake, both for at least a one month period of time. Narcolepsy involves cataplexy and/ or automatic REM. While Dyssonmias focus on initiating and remaining asleep, the Parasomnias are sleep disorders associated with behavioral abnormalities and/ or physiological occurrences. Parasomnias are Nightmare Disorder, Sleep Terror Disorder, Sleepwalking Disorder, and Parasomnias Not Otherwise Specified. The sleep disorders related to another mental disorder involve sleep difficulties due to Axis I (Clinical Disorders) or Axis II (Personality Disorders or Mental Retardation). The following review focuses on insomnia, and somewhat on primary sleep disorders in general in relation to the biological and sociocultural models.

	 The biological model of sleep disorders focuses on genes, heritable factors, and physiologically acquired aspect of sleep disorders. Neurons in the hypothalamus containing orexin are responsible for the regulation of sleep and wakefulness. This study experimented with mice and found that there are phenotypic GABAB receptors on the orexin neurons which are specifically responsible for sleep/ wake states. The activation of the GABAA receptor induces responses that promote sleep. If it is inhibited from firing, this can cause reduced anxiety and induce sleep. The GABAB agonist (baclofen) increased sleep time (Matsuki et al., 2009). Such results imply that the animal models of mice can be generalized to studies in humans.
